description.text: Nothing special just a test

And the 3d printer saves the day yet again!
A family member lost the back to a wrist watch. It was a watch he enjoyed wearing and has been searching real hard on the internet for a replacement back. I offered to try and print him one.... half expecting to fail miserably.
To my surprised, it actually worked really well. The replacement snaps in and stays in! You can tell I wasn't expecting it to work because of the bright blue color I printed in. :]
I know this is definitely not a permanent replacement. And I didn't have an o-ring or anything so I doubt it would fair well in a wet environment. But it is a good solution so he can wear the watch while looking and waiting for a replacement to arrive.

I don't expect anyone has the same watch and if they do, I wouldn't expect that they lost the back to it. This is more of a proof of concept.
I wanted to post it because I was so amazed that it worked and hopefully, it will inspire someone else to use this temporary fix one day if their watch breaks.
The scad file and .stl file generate four different backs. Each one with a different method I thought might work for getting it to snap in. Turns out, Back1() and Back2() or the ones with the little cubes or triangles sticking out of the rim worked the best for snapping in.
The other two, didn't work at all. They were tapered outward toward the top, and it just didn't end up working out.
So, if you have a citizen watch that looks like the one pictured. Use the backs with the tiny cubes sticking out or the tiny triangles sticking out!

I had a hard time customizing the box, so I took most of the ideas and rewrote the OpenSCAD code from scratch. (And learned a lot about the limitations and undocumented parts of the language...)
The holes are now defined inside a list, so you don't have to define them twice.  There's still some features missing from the original.

Determine the size of your package, and where the holes need to be. Modify the scad file.
  • Change the INNER_{LENGTH,WIDTH,HEIGHT} and TOP_HEIGHT variables to define the inner dimensions, and where the top/bottom split is.
  • Change the WALL_THICKNESS, LIP_HEIGHT, CORNER_RADIUS, CURVE_SIDES variables to tweak the box thickness, the fit, and how curvy (or not) the sides are.
  • Define the holes (rounded rectangle or cylinder/cone) using a list.

comments.text: This model was made from a picture off the internet.  Its a height map, made using a picture drawn, or painted with shades of gray.  The darker the color, the higher the image will extrude.   I use a free software app called BMP2IGES.  Its a German program in English.   You could also use Microsofts 3d builder which is free with win 10.  I used Paint.net to convert the pic to black and white, re-traced the outlines in black, used a soft blur on the image to insure a smooth model.  Bmp2iges will convert the image into an STL and save.  I then used Netfabb studio free to cut the image from its background.  I then usually import the model into Repetier so I can see it on the print bed, then re-size it for printing...All the items I have created, I just used different free software packages to do different things to  the STL's.

description.text:
This carriage is great.  
I have made a ton of prototypes and done a lot of work to come to this design, and I'm really happy with it.  
It's designed to work with two 50mm centrifugal fans and gives an absurd amount of cooling for all of your 89 degree overhang needs.

The construction is partly intuitive, find bolts and nuts that fit everything well. The belt clamp that I use is the Crushinator (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:184634) which holds the belt very tightly and allows me to keep the belt very taut. The fan on the front is a regular 40mm computer fan which I cut the bottom corners off of with a Dremel. I think that these are the centrifugal fans that I have: http://amzn.com/B00H8VV0XK And I had to use a relay because they're 24v, not 12v, but it was worth it for the price. I control their strength with a variable resistor. There is some heat resistant tape that is necessary for this build. I will try to get some pictures up soon for this process. It was necessary for me to insulate and direct air away from the nozzle block with heat resistant tape, because the centrifugal fans are very capable of keeping the nozzle much too cool.

title: Launch Platform for DJI Phantom 2 vision plus.. Alternative to an 8th channel expense
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Ok guys.. Vs 8 success! If you own a DJI Phantom and a 3d printer (or access to one).. Here is your alternative to another $350+ channel to do the same thing here for less than $20 and print filament etc.. Launch something from above.. Vs 8.. Notice.. No flight characteristic changes with landing gear/gimbel guard.. With Launch platform: I'm happy to announce 11 flights in a row with zero changes in flight characteristics.. Hehe.. The only noticeable difference was flight time seemed reduced to about 17+ mins.. Weights: Landing Gear/Gimbel Guard: 49 gms.. Empty 'Balanced' Snap on Launch Platform: 114 gms.. Total 163 gms..
Note.. Currently working to determine if a long hinge micro switch and fulcrum might be more efficient than a brush system while considering the additional strain on the gimbel system.. Also 6v vs 3v power..

The stl files are arranged in the best print configuration for my machine (XYZ).. Depending on your printers capabilities to print near perfect circles you may find better print orientations.. The basic landing gear and Gimbel protector is a single print.. It  mounts fine with 2 small cable ties..   
Super glue is used to bind the sides to bottom 'A', bottom 'B' (print 2) to the balance rails of bottom 'A', the contact boom to the back of the container, the motor housing to the container, the motor spindle is a 'pressed' fit.. the latchmec slide to the Ejector and the Latch Pin/Circuit breaker to the back of the platform (cock and load for launch and then glue the Pre-assembled Latch Pin/circuit breaker)..  
I used double sided tape to attach the 3v battery housing.. Use 'C' shaped cuts from a 'Jumbo' paper clip for hinges when coupling LatchMec 'T' Pusher to Ejector LatchMec and for hinging the 'Retainer' to the bottom of container.. A cut jumbo paper clip was used to serve as both a latch Pin and circuit breaker (Make sure to file any sharp edges from your cut paper clip to prevent tearing the conductive tape and promote smooth electrical contact).. I used a small piece of conductive tape around the loop end of the paper clip/circuit breaker to solder the wiring to the paper clip and mount in the designated Pin/latch holder..   
The motor housing and spindle is for the 'geared' motor displayed with a 2.1mm shaft.. Brushes were made by cutting the sides from 1/2 in brass pipe screens and crimping one end to solder and then glued to the contact boom..   
I like a thick viscosity super glue like Mighty Mendit for attaching brushes and securing wiring.. Medium sit epoxy will work as well.. Make a cable for the motor spindle from twine or whatever medium you prefer..   
When building the Latch Mec Circuit breaker and battery assembly use multiple layers of conductive tape to determine the 'fit' you prefer.. Placement of the 'conductive' tape in the bottom corner of the camera shell will result in contact when the camera is pointed all the way down for launching whatever you can fit! Snicker.. Please note rubber band 'routing' for proper operation..   
The 'Counter weight compartments are designed for 1/4 inch flat washers.. When completely assembled use the balance points on the bottom of the launch platform and load 1/4" washers to find a slight forward balance when empty.. My prototype took 8 washers on the battery side to 6 on the motor side (Diff between motor weight and battery assb weight)..   
Total weight of Landing gear and empty 'balanced' launch platform was 163 gms.. Most agree the Phantom 2 will lift 450 grms without running hot and only moderate fight time decrease.. That leaves over 250 grams of lift without problems.. Use the Launch Balance Mec to determine your 'load' balance after cocking and before snapping in.. Add washers to compensate for your load.. Printing of the Storage Brush protector is optional to operation.. 3d Max Studio files available upon request.. Have fun guys.. I included an .stl of a Tissue paper streamer that holds a 'Disc Golf Beacon light'.. 5 foot of tissue paper can be 'roll filled' with lots of multicolor confetti and other things.. Snicker..

USB90Î¼C: a minimal development board for the Atmel AT90USB162 USB enabled microcontroller. This is a cleaned up version of a home-designed-and-built development board used to learn how to interface to and write programs for the AT90USB162 microcontroller. A pic of the first home-built version can be seen at http://www.flickr.com/photos/everydayinventors/5368101007/ . With the exception of the AVR mcu, all parts are through-hole for ease of assembly. If you don't wish to manufacture a bare PCB yourself, you can get one from BatchPCB: http://www.batchpcb.com/index.php/Products/61022

Device program flash and EEPROM can be programmed over USB using Atmel FLIP ( http://www.atmel.com/dyn/products/tools_card.asp?tool_id=3886 ) or the open dfu-programmer ( http://dfu-programmer.sourceforge.net/ ) software. Programs can be written in C using GCC for AVR target ( http://www.nongnu.org/avr-libc/ ). A very good AVR USB library with many examples is Dean Camera's Lightweight USB Framework for AVRs ( http://www.fourwalledcubicle.com/LUFA.php ). Ubuntu GNU/Linux 10.04 LTS users can install both dfu-programmer and gcc-avr using the Ubuntu Software Center or Synaptic Package Manager. A simple example test program written in C is included. Alternate repository for schematics and source code at GitHub:
https://github.com/EverydayInventors/USB90uC

comments.text: Right, no external programmer, just a USB cable is all you need. The AT90USB162 device comes from the factory with a 4k USB device-flash-update bootloader already installed.  The first time it is powered up, it waits for a program and/or data to write to its non-volatile program flash and data EEPROM memories.   Once uploaded and on subsequent device resets, it jumps to the user program written into flash memory.  If you wish to overwrite the user program, just hold down the DFU button and briefly press he Reset button and it will re-enter the USB device-flash-update bootloader to await an upload.

description.text: This Solar Burner Tube will collect sun light and focus it in a small point at the smaller end of the tube. You will have to coat the inner surface with a reflecting material. For me a reflecting tape worked well enough to melt black plastic. I guess, the Solar Burner Tube (h40fa18)  can increase the sun light's energy density by a factor of 45.

Warning:
Never look into the focused light spot. Regular sun glasses will not prevent eye damage. You will need a professional eye protection. Store it in a fire prove place like a metal box. First check out "Maximum permissible exposure":
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laser_safety The power density of the sun on earth is about 0.1 W/cm^2. A maximum of 0.001 W is defined to be save in Laser Class 2 (pupil's surface = 0.39 cm^2). You should never look directly into the sun. And you should never look at a 45 times stronger light source, too. Some calculations for version h40fa18 :
My Solar Burner Tube's effective area is A_top - A_bottom = 55.4 cm^2 - 10.2 cm^2 = 45.2 cm^2. Let's say the focus area size is about 1 cm^2. That's up to 4.52 W focused in 1 cm^2.
Well, tell me if there are mistakes in the calculations.

About the surface: My printer doesn't produce a smooth surface. I always can feel the lines of the print. But a mirroring surface needs to be very smooth.
By Using a mirroring tape from the hardware store, I had my best results. I uploaded some pictures of the narrow tube. I tried to cover the surface by a mirroring paint. But as you can see, the paint doesn't stick to it. The ripples lead to a scattering surface. There is no mirror effect by this coating. Then I tried to melt the surface by a flame. But this leads to a deformation.
